data.content:
Your test works but uses generic `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere, which produces unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False." MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Before | After | Benefit |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows expected vs actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Failure explains 0 or 2+ matches found |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` line is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate," so `IsTrue` is appropriate there.

Other quick wins for the test class: mark it `sealed` and consider renaming to `UserServiceTests` if it isn't already.
